        page_content="A:  SLR  is  the  minimum  percentage  of  NDTL  that  banks  must  maintain  in  liquid  assets  (cash,  \ngold,\n \nor\n \nRBI-approved\n \nsecurities).\n \nCurrently\n \n18%.\n Source:  Banking  Regulation  Act,  1949,  Section  24   Q79:  What  is  the  Priority  Sector  Lending  (PSL)  target  for  domestic  commercial  banks?  A:  40%  of  Adjusted  Net  Bank  Credit  (ANBC)  or  Credit  Equivalent  of  Off-Balance  Sheet  \nExposures,\n \nwhichever\n \nis\n \nhigher.\n Source:  RBI  Master  Directions  on  PSL,  2020   Q80:  What  are  the  sub-targets  within  Priority  Sector  Lending?  A:  Agriculture:  18%  (of  which  small/marginal  farmers:  10%).  Micro  enterprises:  7.5%.  Weaker  \nsections:\n \n12%.\n \nEconomic\n \nWeaker\n \nSection\n \n(EWS):\n \nincluded\n \nin\n \nweaker\n \nsections.\n Source:  RBI  PSL  Master  Directions   ---   ##  SECTION  9:  Risk  Management  &  Governance   Q81:  What  is  the  CAMELS  framework  used  by  RBI?  A:  CAMELS  rates  banks  on:  Capital  Adequacy,  Asset  Quality,  Management,  Earnings,  Liquidity,  \nand\n \nSystems\n \n&\n \nControls\n \n(Sensitivity\n \nto\n \nMarket\n \nRisk).\n \nUsed\n \nduring\n \nRBI\n \non-site\n \ninspections.\n Source:  RBI  Supervisory  Framework  (SPARC)   Q82:  What  is  the  Risk-Based  Supervision  (RBS)  approach?  A:  RBS  focuses  supervisory  resources  on  high-risk  banks.  RBI  uses  SPARC  (Supervisory  \nProgramme\n \nfor\n \nAssessment\n \nof\n \nRisk\n \nand\n \nCapital)\n \nfor\n \nforward-looking\n \nrisk\n \nassessment.\n Source:  RBI  Supervisory  Framework   Q83:  What  are  Early  Warning  Signals  (EWS)  for  NPA  detection?  A:  EWS  include:  non-submission  of  stock  statements,  frequent  ad-hoc  credit  requests,  \ndeteriorating\n \nfinancial\n \nratios,\n \ndelays\n \nin\n \ndebt\n \nservicing,\n \nand\n \nunusual\n \ncash\n \ntransactions.\n Source:  RBI  Fraud  Risk  Management  Guidelines;  RBI  Circular  on  EWS   Q84:  What  is  a  Red  Flagged  Account  (RFA)?  A:  An  account  flagged  based  on  EWS  with  suspicion  of  fraud.  Banks  must  report  RFAs  to  \nCRILC\n \nand\n \nescalate\n \nto\n \nSpecial\n \nMention\n \nAccount\n \n(SMA)\n \ncategory.\n Source:  RBI  Fraud  Monitoring  Guidelines   Q85:  What  is  the  CRILC  reporting  framework?  A:  Central  Repository  of  Information  on  Large  Credits  (CRILC)  requires  banks  to  report  all  \nborrower\n \nexposures\n \n≥\n \n₹5\n \ncrore\n \nquarterly,\n \nand\n \nimmediately\n \non\n \nSMA-2\n \nor\n \nNPA\n \nclassification.\n Source:  RBI  CRILC  Circular,  2014   Q86:  What  is  Concentration  Risk  and  how  should  banks  manage  it?",
